<header class="header">
  <h1>How to Plan a Garden in a Short Growing Season</h1>

  <p class="tagline">
    Short seasons don’t require luck — they require modeling.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    In a typical year, your growing season is bounded by frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong>.
    In short-season climates, success depends on how much time — and how much heat — accumulates before frost returns.
  </p>

  <p>
    Many short-season gardens fail for a simple reason:
    gardeners rely on calendar advice instead of climate constraints.
  </p>

  <p>
    A crop labeled “90 days to maturity” may appear safe in a 100-day frost-free season.
    But if seasonal heat accumulation is low, that crop may still reach the frost boundary before maturity.
  </p>

  <p>
    Short-season planning requires a structured sequence:
    <strong>Frost → Season Length → Growing Degree Days → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin</strong>.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Counts as a Short Growing Season?</h2>

  <p>
    Frost dates are based on <strong>1991–2020 climate normals</strong>
    and expressed at the <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
    That means the listed dates represent typical timing — not a guarantee.
  </p>

  <p>
    A short growing season usually includes:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>90–120 frost-free days</li>
    <li>Late last spring frost</li>
    <li>Early first fall frost</li>
    <li>Cool early and late-season temperatures</li>
    <li>Lower total seasonal heat accumulation</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    You can identify your frost boundaries using the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    But frost-free days alone are not the real constraint.
    The real constraint is how much usable heat accumulates inside that window.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Frost Boundary Defines Your Planning Window</h2>

  <p>
    Two events define your climate boundary:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Last spring frost (32°F / 0°C)</strong></li>
    <li><strong>First fall frost (32°F / 0°C)</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    At the 50% probability level, about half of years will see frost earlier or later than these dates.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short climates, the window between these boundaries is narrow.
    Every week inside that window carries more weight.
  </p>

  <p>
    When planning near the boundary, small timing errors compound quickly.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Calendar Logic Breaks Down</h2>

  <p>
    Seed packets and regional calendars list “days to maturity.”
    That number assumes average warmth.
  </p>

  <p>
    Consider a 100-day frost-free season:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Tomato labeled 95 days</li>
    <li>Planted immediately after last frost</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    On paper, it fits.
  </p>

  <p>
    But if seasonal heat accumulation is only 1,500–1,600 GDD (base 50°F),
    and the variety requires 1,800 GDD,
    the crop reaches the frost boundary before fully maturing.
  </p>

  <p>
    The calendar was correct.
    The heat budget was not.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is explained further in
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Your Seasonal Heat Budget (Growing Degree Days)</h2>

  <p>
    Growing Degree Days (GDD) measure accumulated heat.
    Most warm-season crops use a base of <strong>50°F (10°C)</strong>.
  </p>

  <pre>
GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </pre>

  <p>
    Each day above the base threshold contributes heat units.
    Over the frost-free window, those units accumulate into your seasonal heat budget.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate available GDD before first frost using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short-season climates, total seasonal GDD often becomes the limiting factor —
    not just frost-free days.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Crop Heat Demand Tiers</h2>

  <p>
    Crops vary widely in seasonal heat requirements:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Low heat demand:</strong> Under ~1,200 GDD (lettuce, spinach, radishes)</li>
    <li><strong>Moderate heat demand:</strong> ~1,200–1,800 GDD (beans, zucchini)</li>
    <li><strong>High heat demand:</strong> 2,000+ GDD (large tomatoes, winter squash, long-season sweet corn)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Within each crop, variety differences can exceed several hundred GDD.
    For example, tomato cultivars can range from ~1,200 to over 2,000 GDD.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your seasonal heat budget falls below a crop’s requirement,
    the mismatch is structural — not a matter of better timing.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Applied Scenario Modeling</h2>

  <p><strong>Scenario A — 2,300 GDD Available</strong><br>
  Most tomato varieties mature comfortably.<br>
  Winter squash at 2,200 GDD operates near the boundary but remains feasible.</p>

  <p><strong>Scenario B — 1,800 GDD Available</strong><br>
  Short-season tomatoes (~1,400–1,600 GDD) mature reliably.<br>
  Long-season heirlooms (~2,000+ GDD) become borderline.</p>

  <p><strong>Scenario C — 1,400 GDD Available</strong><br>
  Cool-season crops thrive.<br>
  High-heat crops are structurally mismatched to the climate.</p>

  <p>
    Notice that frost-free days may be similar across these scenarios.
    The heat budget determines feasibility.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Risk Margin Near the Frost Boundary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Comfortable:</strong> Seasonal GDD exceeds requirement by several hundred units.</li>
    <li><strong>Borderline:</strong> Requirement closely matches available GDD.</li>
    <li><strong>Unlikely:</strong> Available GDD typically falls short.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Because frost dates use probability framing,
    cooler-than-typical summers or earlier-than-typical fall frosts reduce margin.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short climates, planning with margin is often more important than maximizing ambition.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Can You Extend a Short Season?</h2>

  <p>
    Indoor seed starting and row covers can reduce frost exposure risk.
    You can coordinate transplant timing using the
    <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Start Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    However, protection methods primarily shift frost exposure.
    They do <strong>not materially increase cumulative seasonal GDD</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    They improve margin.
    They do not convert a low-heat climate into a high-heat one.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Short-Season Planning Model</h2>

  <ol>
    <li>Identify frost boundaries at 32°F (50% probability).</li>
    <li>Define your frost-free window.</li>
    <li>Estimate total seasonal GDD before first frost.</li>
    <li>Compare crop heat requirements.</li>
    <li>Choose your risk margin.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    When frost timing and heat accumulation align with crop requirements,
    maturity becomes predictable in a typical year.
  </p>

  <p>
    When they do not,
    calendar-based planting advice often fails.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Short seasons are constrained by frost timing and limited heat accumulation.</li>
    <li>Frost boundaries use a 32°F definition and 50% probability framing.</li>
    <li>Growing Degree Days define your seasonal heat budget.</li>
    <li>Crop feasibility depends on matching heat requirement to heat budget.</li>
    <li>Risk margin determines reliability near the frost boundary.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In short climates, success comes from modeling constraints —
    not relying on calendar labels.
  </p>
</section>